DON WALSH: Yeah, I'm
not put off by people

00:57:53.580 --> 00:57:55.260
getting up and walking out.

00:57:55.260 --> 00:57:58.210
I've been doing this for a long
time and I'm quite used to it.

00:57:58.210 --> 00:58:00.340
I did a high school
in Tyler, Texas once

00:58:00.340 --> 00:58:02.540
and I asked the principal
how long, he told me.

00:58:02.540 --> 00:58:04.620
And I thought, OK,
I'll stick right on it.

00:58:04.620 --> 00:58:08.760
It's like salami, you just
slice off as much as they need.

00:58:08.760 --> 00:58:11.100
But about halfway
through a lot of bells

00:58:11.100 --> 00:58:13.846
rang and my whole audience
got up and walked out.

00:58:13.846 --> 00:58:15.220
It was the end of
the school day.

00:58:15.220 --> 00:58:17.770
They had their priorities.

00:58:17.770 --> 00:58:19.790
That's why they're in Texas.

00:58:19.790 --> 00:58:20.290
Yes, sir.

00:58:20.290 --> 00:58:21.980
AUDIENCE: Is it an
incremental challenge

00:58:21.980 --> 00:58:25.360
to go from 20,000 to 35,000
feet engineering wise,

00:58:25.360 --> 00:58:28.542
or is there something that
comes up at 25,000 feet

00:58:28.542 --> 00:58:30.430
that requires a whole
different approach?

00:58:30.430 --> 00:58:32.930
DON WALSH: His question was
is it an incremental challenge

00:58:32.930 --> 00:58:36.840
to go, say, from 25,000
to 35,000, 36,000 feet.

00:58:36.840 --> 00:58:38.930
In my view, no.

00:58:38.930 --> 00:58:41.520
I ask Woods Hole about that
when they're upgrading Alvins.

00:58:41.520 --> 00:58:43.020
You may know Alvin
is being upgraded

00:58:43.020 --> 00:58:49.990
from 14,500 feet, something like
that, too about 24,000 feet.

00:58:49.990 --> 00:58:54.320
It'll be the second deepest
diving manned submersible.

00:58:54.320 --> 00:58:56.480
Thing is, they got
Lockheed Martin involved

00:58:56.480 --> 00:58:58.310
and all the money got spent.

00:58:58.310 --> 00:59:02.440
So what you've got now is
you've got a 24,000 foot

00:59:02.440 --> 00:59:07.490
cabin in a 14,000 foot sub
because all their peripherals--

00:59:07.490 --> 00:59:10.080
because you have other
pressure vessels in there

00:59:10.080 --> 00:59:11.515
for the batteries
and controllers,

00:59:11.515 --> 00:59:12.390
and things like that.

00:59:12.390 --> 00:59:14.310
And they couldn't
upgrade the whole sub.

00:59:14.310 --> 00:59:16.170
And probably syntactic
foam, I don't know.

00:59:16.170 --> 00:59:18.810
But anyway, they spent
the whole $25 million

00:59:18.810 --> 00:59:22.410
or whatever it was and never
got the thing finished.

00:59:22.410 --> 00:59:25.034
I suspect some year
they'll do that.

00:59:25.034 --> 00:59:26.200
But I asked them about this.

00:59:26.200 --> 00:59:27.780
Well, why not just
go the full depth?

00:59:27.780 --> 00:59:29.210
You don't have to
do it every day,

00:59:29.210 --> 00:59:31.737
but if you want to go
into the deep trenches

00:59:31.737 --> 00:59:32.820
you've got the capability.

00:59:32.820 --> 00:59:34.490
Because most of
the deep trenches,

00:59:34.490 --> 00:59:37.770
between 28,000 and
36,000 feet, there's

00:59:37.770 --> 00:59:42.100
not that much difference between
the deep places in the ocean.

00:59:42.100 --> 00:59:45.980
And that would be an awfully
nice capability to have.

00:59:45.980 --> 00:59:49.080
And they said, well ho
and hum about technical,

00:59:49.080 --> 00:59:51.880
and we can't-- I listened to
what they said and I still

00:59:51.880 --> 00:59:55.000
can't see the difference.

00:59:55.000 --> 00:59:57.950
Your problem is pressure.

00:59:57.950 --> 01:00:01.200
You've got to make a
robust hull, you've

01:00:01.200 --> 01:00:03.070
got to have electric
power, whether it's

01:00:03.070 --> 01:00:07.950
for 25,000 or 36,000 feet,
you want as much as you get.

01:00:07.950 --> 01:00:11.210
And with these new batteries
that are coming out-- again,

01:00:11.210 --> 01:00:14.920
that's the march of material
science-- you can do that.

01:00:14.920 --> 01:00:18.450
So that's a constant.

01:00:18.450 --> 01:00:22.080
The only delta I can see is
the thickness of the hull.

01:00:22.080 --> 01:00:23.820
Titanium, something like that.

01:00:23.820 --> 01:00:26.960
I don't understand
it, so I say no.

01:00:26.960 --> 01:00:28.850
There's no real difference.

01:00:28.850 --> 01:00:30.272
It will be cost difference.

01:00:30.272 --> 01:00:32.730
And of course every one of
these has to have a mother ship.

01:00:32.730 --> 01:00:35.670
It's even better if you have
a dedicated mother ship.

01:00:35.670 --> 01:00:38.820
The two Mirs have a
ship called the Keldysh,

01:00:38.820 --> 01:00:40.290
that's all it does.

01:00:40.290 --> 01:00:43.300
Basically Atlantis, they claim
it's an oceanographic ship,

01:00:43.300 --> 01:00:45.260
but it's pretty much
dedicated to Alvin.

01:00:45.260 --> 01:00:47.460
By the way, they're
in San Francisco now,

01:00:47.460 --> 01:00:50.200
or maybe San Diego.

01:00:50.200 --> 01:00:52.550
Before they did the sea
trial on the new hull,

01:00:52.550 --> 01:00:54.360
they just sent it all out here.

01:00:54.360 --> 01:00:56.050
And they were in
Astoria, and then they

01:00:56.050 --> 01:00:57.652
were supposed to be
in San Francisco,

01:00:57.652 --> 01:00:59.360
and then they're going
down to San Diego.

01:00:59.360 --> 01:01:01.450
And sometime along
the west coast here

01:01:01.450 --> 01:01:04.250
they'll do their actual
acceptance trials.

01:01:04.250 --> 01:01:05.680
Alvin is owned by
the Navy so they

01:01:05.680 --> 01:01:09.730
have some pretty high standards
about what they have to do.

01:01:09.730 --> 01:01:10.590
Yes, sir.

01:01:10.590 --> 01:01:13.416
AUDIENCE: You talked a bit about
going down to the [INAUDIBLE]

01:01:13.416 --> 01:01:16.148
and stuff like that
and all the life forms

01:01:16.148 --> 01:01:18.350
and all this activity
happening there.

01:01:18.350 --> 01:01:22.384
And the minerals and stuff like
that that make it worthwhile.

01:01:22.384 --> 01:01:23.848
What about going
into the trenches?

01:01:23.848 --> 01:01:25.312
What do you see down there?

01:01:25.312 --> 01:01:27.752
And what is it that's so
interesting about going

01:01:27.752 --> 01:01:30.676
to those depths?

01:01:30.676 --> 01:01:33.050
DON WALSH: It's not going to
be a very satisfying answer.

01:01:33.050 --> 01:01:37.730
And that is it's what we
don't know is why we go.

01:01:37.730 --> 01:01:42.100
Jim made a very successful
dive in the Bismarck Trench

01:01:42.100 --> 01:01:45.130
at Papua New Guinea,
about 27,000 feet.

01:01:45.130 --> 01:01:47.350
That's when he
lifted the embargo

01:01:47.350 --> 01:01:48.860
on the design of
his sub and what

01:01:48.860 --> 01:01:50.110
they were going to do with it.

01:01:50.110 --> 01:01:52.068
He didn't want a lot of
press piling in on him.

01:01:52.068 --> 01:01:54.440
There were only 30
people in his project.

01:01:54.440 --> 01:01:55.560
Also the embarrassment.

01:01:55.560 --> 01:01:57.500
When you're a very
high visibility person

01:01:57.500 --> 01:02:00.260
and you fail at something,
everybody says, you see,

01:02:00.260 --> 01:02:02.920
Hollywood guy showboating
and trying to buy his way in,

01:02:02.920 --> 01:02:03.795
and blah, blah, blah.

01:02:03.795 --> 01:02:06.090
That's of course not
true in Jim's case.

01:02:06.090 --> 01:02:08.720
Nevertheless, at that
dive he brought up

01:02:08.720 --> 01:02:12.170
quite a bit of bottom
sediments from that trench.

01:02:12.170 --> 01:02:18.120
And we had a staff of, I
believe, 13 scientists aboard.

01:02:18.120 --> 01:02:21.000
Mostly from Scripp, and
another ship with us

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:23.125
inappropriately
called Barracuda.

01:02:23.125 --> 01:02:26.900
It should have been The Gummy
Bear or something like that.

01:02:26.900 --> 01:02:28.880
It was pretty bad.

01:02:28.880 --> 01:02:32.880
And so we had biologists,
benthic biologists, geologists,

01:02:32.880 --> 01:02:33.910
and so on with us.

01:02:33.910 --> 01:02:36.730
And they were really
excited about getting

01:02:36.730 --> 01:02:38.530
these sediment
samples of microbes.

01:02:38.530 --> 01:02:41.770
They're finding there new stuff
that we didn't know about.

01:02:41.770 --> 01:02:45.360
And really keen to go back
to the deepest trenches

01:02:45.360 --> 01:02:47.830
and do more of this work.

01:02:47.830 --> 01:02:50.650
As far as large
critters are concerned,

01:02:50.650 --> 01:02:53.300
probably not because the
further you get from land,

01:02:53.300 --> 01:02:55.360
the more sterile the ocean gets.

01:02:55.360 --> 01:02:57.182
It's because of
lack of nutrients.

01:02:57.182 --> 01:02:58.890
Most of the nutrients
are being flushed--

01:02:58.890 --> 01:03:01.110
organic, inorganic
nutrients-- from land.

01:03:01.110 --> 01:03:04.290
So the coastal zone,
continental shelf

01:03:04.290 --> 01:03:06.060
is where you really
hit pay dirt.

01:03:06.060 --> 01:03:11.570
And then a little bit over,
say, the continental crest

01:03:11.570 --> 01:03:14.750
down in the deep ocean,
slope into the deep ocean.

01:03:14.750 --> 01:03:18.740
So 200 miles off
land, not so great.

01:03:18.740 --> 01:03:19.600
Sort of a desert.

01:03:19.600 --> 01:03:20.600
There's life everywhere.

01:03:20.600 --> 01:03:25.180
You get all the invertebrates.

01:03:25.180 --> 01:03:27.870
The shrimps, the jellies, things
like that, and bioluminesence,

01:03:27.870 --> 01:03:29.495
when you've got the
light's turned out,

01:03:29.495 --> 01:03:30.440
things sparkling away.

01:03:30.440 --> 01:03:35.320
But compared to what you see
the coastal ocean it's not much.

01:03:35.320 --> 01:03:37.250
There is, as you
probably know, they

01:03:37.250 --> 01:03:39.330
did some really
wonderful photography

01:03:39.330 --> 01:03:42.690
of the giant squid recently
from a submersible.

01:03:42.690 --> 01:03:44.480
Really good stuff.

01:03:44.480 --> 01:03:47.320
But just when you think
you've seen it all,

01:03:47.320 --> 01:03:49.530
when you've seen
the movie, they've

01:03:49.530 --> 01:03:53.460
determined that there is a
colossal squid because they've

01:03:53.460 --> 01:03:56.759
seen some of these bits of these
things drift up on beaches.

01:03:56.759 --> 01:03:58.300
They haven't seen
one in [INAUDIBLE].

01:03:58.300 --> 01:04:01.410
The wonderful imagery they got
recently of the giant squid

01:04:01.410 --> 01:04:02.220
was in [INAUDIBLE].

01:04:02.220 --> 01:04:03.803
They put out bait
from the submersible

01:04:03.803 --> 01:04:05.150
and it came in and took.

01:04:05.150 --> 01:04:06.730
And got comfortable
with the lights,

01:04:06.730 --> 01:04:07.855
it was just hanging around.

01:04:07.855 --> 01:04:09.520
It was really something.

01:04:09.520 --> 01:04:14.820
So I think probably a
lot of the discoveries

01:04:14.820 --> 01:04:18.810
will be in the microbiology
and microplankton area

01:04:18.810 --> 01:04:21.220
and what's contained
in those sediments.

01:04:21.220 --> 01:04:23.830
Regrettably, on Jim's
dive in the Challenger

01:04:23.830 --> 01:04:29.390
Deep-- and it's Murphy's Law.

01:04:29.390 --> 01:04:31.840
He had just started to
pick up samples, sediment.

01:04:31.840 --> 01:04:35.210
He had core tubes so he could
push them into the bottom,

01:04:35.210 --> 01:04:37.700
bring them up, and then
he had a little cupboard

01:04:37.700 --> 01:04:39.552
where he could sequester them.

01:04:39.552 --> 01:04:42.010
Because as you come back up,
you've got a lot of turbulence

01:04:42.010 --> 01:04:42.740
around the sub.

01:04:42.740 --> 01:04:45.031
And you just flush it all
out so you lose your samples.

01:04:45.031 --> 01:04:48.170
So that was all designed into
that to protect this stuff.

01:04:48.170 --> 01:04:50.790
And he was just reaching
out for another one and one

01:04:50.790 --> 01:04:52.620
the hydraulic hoses broke.

01:04:52.620 --> 01:04:56.180
Now arthritis sets in,
the manipulator's here.

01:04:56.180 --> 01:04:59.710
He can't shut the door to
the cupboard, if you will,

01:04:59.710 --> 01:05:02.730
and he can't take samples.

01:05:02.730 --> 01:05:06.560
And it was is a $50 hose that
screwed up a billion dollar

01:05:06.560 --> 01:05:07.060
project.

01:05:07.060 --> 01:05:08.893
We see it all the time
in the space program.

01:05:08.893 --> 01:05:10.450
Standard stuff.

01:05:10.450 --> 01:05:14.780
Pressure tested,
qualified by the vendor,

01:05:14.780 --> 01:05:17.240
and tested again by
Jim and his team.

01:05:17.240 --> 01:05:19.430
Just a simple hydraulic hose.

01:05:19.430 --> 01:05:21.670
And that crippled that mission.

01:05:21.670 --> 01:05:23.720
Then due to
programming errors, he

01:05:23.720 --> 01:05:27.680
had 12 thrusters and
11 of them shut down.

01:05:27.680 --> 01:05:31.654
So all he could do is circle,
make circles on the sea floor.

01:05:31.654 --> 01:05:32.320
And that was it.

01:05:32.320 --> 01:05:34.680
So it was not a very
productive dive.

01:05:34.680 --> 01:05:39.290
But the one in Bismarck
trench was very productive.

01:05:39.290 --> 01:05:42.060
And what was his name?

01:05:42.060 --> 01:05:44.200
Wake up.

01:05:44.200 --> 01:05:45.020
The guy at Scripps.

01:05:48.075 --> 01:05:49.075
AUDIENCE: Doug Bartlett.

01:05:49.075 --> 01:05:49.330
DON WALSH: Doug Bartlett.

01:05:49.330 --> 01:05:50.387
Thank you.

01:05:50.387 --> 01:05:52.470
Doug's doing some good
work and some of his papers

01:05:52.470 --> 01:05:54.260
will be out soon.

01:05:54.260 --> 01:05:56.410
And we do hope to go back.

01:05:56.410 --> 01:05:59.020
If not with manned
system, unmanned system.

01:05:59.020 --> 01:06:01.909
We the ocean community, not me.

01:06:01.909 --> 01:06:03.450
I don't know if
that's a good answer,

01:06:03.450 --> 01:06:06.570
but the top answer
is we go there

01:06:06.570 --> 01:06:09.300
because we don't
know what we'll find.

01:06:09.300 --> 01:06:10.690
That's the nature
of exploration.

01:06:10.690 --> 01:06:15.030
I define exploration as
curiosity acted upon.

01:06:15.030 --> 01:06:17.362
We're all curious about stuff
we run into all the time.

01:06:17.362 --> 01:06:19.320
Oh that's interesting,
I wonder how that works.

01:06:19.320 --> 01:06:21.653
But if you don't follow up
on it, find out how it works,

01:06:21.653 --> 01:06:24.530
why it works, then
you're not an explorer.

01:06:24.530 --> 01:06:26.460
I think little
kids are explorers.

01:06:26.460 --> 01:06:28.645
We're all genetically
programmed that way.

01:06:28.645 --> 01:06:30.770
You see them in their
mother's arms looking around.

01:06:30.770 --> 01:06:32.240
When they're big
enough to run around.

01:06:32.240 --> 01:06:34.198
they're taking the gum
off the bottom the table

01:06:34.198 --> 01:06:36.750
in a restaurant and
they're exploring that way.

01:06:36.750 --> 01:06:40.660
But somehow that the hormones
and peer pressures in the teens

01:06:40.660 --> 01:06:42.380
beat out of most of us.

01:06:42.380 --> 01:06:47.880
A lot of us don't persist as
explores until our adult years.

01:06:47.880 --> 01:06:49.465
See I don't use
the term explorer

01:06:49.465 --> 01:06:52.250
as climbing the highest
or diving to the deepest.

01:06:52.250 --> 01:06:56.500
It's curious people learning
how things work on our planet.

01:06:56.500 --> 01:06:57.970
And even if you're
not a scientist,

01:06:57.970 --> 01:07:01.891
it's so important to be curious
about the world around you.

01:07:01.891 --> 01:07:02.390
Yes sir.

01:07:02.390 --> 01:07:04.238
AUDIENCE: What do you see
as interesting developments

01:07:04.238 --> 01:07:05.624
in the next 10 or 25 years?

01:07:08.592 --> 01:07:10.050
DON WALSH: I think
what we're going

01:07:10.050 --> 01:07:14.070
to see is the development
of, sort of the subject

01:07:14.070 --> 01:07:17.820
I've been talking about, is
a manned submersible system.

01:07:17.820 --> 01:07:20.860
We can't look at these
things as individual units.

01:07:20.860 --> 01:07:21.780
It's a whole system.

01:07:21.780 --> 01:07:23.870
That's the mother ship.

01:07:23.870 --> 01:07:26.990
You should have an ROV along
that has the same depth

01:07:26.990 --> 01:07:29.280
capability so if the
sub gets in trouble

01:07:29.280 --> 01:07:31.510
you've got on-board assistance.

01:07:31.510 --> 01:07:34.810
The model that appeals to me is
the deep sea drilling project

01:07:34.810 --> 01:07:38.210
where a specially
configured drilling

01:07:38.210 --> 01:07:41.995
ship is doing these very
deep geological cores all

01:07:41.995 --> 01:07:42.870
over the world ocean.

01:07:42.870 --> 01:07:45.980
World Ocean Drilling Program.

01:07:45.980 --> 01:07:51.280
And that ship was built by
the United States, operated

01:07:51.280 --> 01:07:52.860
by the National
Science Foundation.

01:07:52.860 --> 01:07:55.516
But we sell tickets
to any investigator

01:07:55.516 --> 01:07:56.390
that wants to use it.

01:07:56.390 --> 01:08:00.200
So even during the Cold War
we had Soviet geoscientists

01:08:00.200 --> 01:08:04.870
out on the ship because
they could buy certain legs.

01:08:04.870 --> 01:08:08.560
You publish the ship's schedule
a year or two in advance

01:08:08.560 --> 01:08:11.760
and then if that's an area
where you really want to work,

01:08:11.760 --> 01:08:14.370
you apply to get
time on that ship.

01:08:14.370 --> 01:08:20.407
I can see that model for a full
ocean depth submersible system.

01:08:20.407 --> 01:08:22.490
Of course you couldn't do
anything less than that,

01:08:22.490 --> 01:08:27.029
but it would be a live-aboard
mother ship, an ROV system,

01:08:27.029 --> 01:08:30.859
and other required
scientific instrumentation.

01:08:30.859 --> 01:08:33.140
And it would be available
as an international asset.

01:08:33.140 --> 01:08:34.931
I don't think you'd
need more than a couple

01:08:34.931 --> 01:08:37.580
of systems of that sort
to do the trenches.

01:08:37.580 --> 01:08:40.840
You don't have to have one,
every country has to own it.

01:08:40.840 --> 01:08:42.640
Just like the deep
sea drilling ships.

01:08:42.640 --> 01:08:46.381
Pretty much that one
system was the only one

01:08:46.381 --> 01:08:49.620
for 90% of the life
of this program.

01:08:49.620 --> 01:08:53.470
Now Japan has one called
Chikyu and the Russians

01:08:53.470 --> 01:08:57.310
keep promising to build one,
but it never seems to happen.

01:08:57.310 --> 01:08:59.961
So there's at least
two in the world now.

01:08:59.961 --> 01:09:00.460
Yes, sir.

01:09:00.460 --> 01:09:01.609
AUDIENCE: India has one.

01:09:01.609 --> 01:09:04.193
DON WALSH: India has one?

01:09:04.193 --> 01:09:05.859
Well, it probably ran
aground somewhere.

01:09:05.859 --> 01:09:06.574
AUDIENCE: No.

01:09:06.574 --> 01:09:08.740
Beautiful. [INAUDIBLE] built
it, so there are three.

01:09:08.740 --> 01:09:09.170
DON WALSH: Is that right?

01:09:09.170 --> 01:09:09.920
OK, three of them.

01:09:09.920 --> 01:09:13.660
India And with respect
to investigating

01:09:13.660 --> 01:09:15.720
the deep trenches, the
thing we're not doing now,

01:09:15.720 --> 01:09:20.260
I still think there's going
to be a lot of heavy lifting

01:09:20.260 --> 01:09:23.460
that's going to be done
by unmanned vehicles.

01:09:23.460 --> 01:09:26.819
The problem here is that
if we agree that about 90%

01:09:26.819 --> 01:09:29.840
of the world ocean is
unexplored in terms

01:09:29.840 --> 01:09:33.630
of having pretty complete
knowledge of this environment,

01:09:33.630 --> 01:09:36.069
that's a big job left to do.

01:09:36.069 --> 01:09:38.790
